name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "It was my first job and it started me on a path through the tech world that shaped me into who I am today. If you have that desire to grow and learn something, you can do anything." (9/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "You can learn anything you're willing to take the time to. If you're willing to learn, we're willing to teach." (8/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "We ended up talking about the software business he owns and how he would love for me to come for an interview. I was skeptical about my ability to do a job where I had no idea how to write code, but his response stuck with me and will continue to for the rest of my life:" (7/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "I told him that I was at a point in my life where I was about to finish college, but I didn't know what was next for me. We talked about my interests in coding and technology, but I really had no experience with writing any code ‚Äî yet I still really wanted to try it." (6/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "And then one single event on one single day changed my life: I went to a wedding. I met a family member of my now wife. He talked to me about my family and life and what I wanted to do with mine." (5/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "Even though I picked a major, all through college I wasn't really sure what I wanted to do with my life or where I wanted to go. I was near graduation with no plan for life after college." (4/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "But where it really started for me professionally was in 2011, when I graduated with a degree in Computer Engineering from the University of Michigan-Dearborn." (3/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: "My journey into tech is one rooted in my curiosity about how things worked and my love for video games as a kid. It inspired me to pursue a degree in engineering." (2/9)

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (7/7) "I'd like to end with an inspirational quote here, as our very own Juned did, but I'll have to just say: We're all humans before we're users; that's the belief I aim to bring to every conversation."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (6/7) "This peek into the human experience and the ability we have to then take that information and use it to build the right thing is supremely rewarding."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (5/7) "This is my favorite part of my role as a User Experience Researcher. I have the privilege of talking with the people who we intend to build something for and find out what it is they need, what their pain points are, and how we can make it better."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (4/7) "The consistent thread between all of this is a focus on the human experience: what people think, how they feel when they see a yellow leaf, the sun goes down, or when they log-in to a website, how they interact with the world around them, & what they need to feel content."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (3/7) "But eons ago, long before the concept of 'users,' I earned a degree in English Literature, edited some books, wrote a lot, and thought a lot about people."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (2/7) "I came into user experience research (which is a fancy way of saying I talk to the people who use the products we're building) from being a developer (s/o to the Detroit Labs Apprenticeship program!)."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (1/7) In this thread, Elle Gover shares how she began her journey as a User Experience Researcher. ‚û°Ô∏è  https://t.co/r6WPWZBMR9

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (9/9) "A lot of things I learned as a Peace Corps volunteer prepared me for a career in tech and directly apply to my job here. The technical things I had to learn, but I always like a challenge."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (8/9) "There was so much exciting stuff going on in Detroit at the time, I figured I would be upset if I didn't come back to Detroit when all of this was happening here."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (7/9) "While I was in SF, I made the decision that it was just not working for me and started cold-emailing a lot of small companies in the Detroit area to get a tour or meet people for coffee."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (6/9) "I always knew I didn't want to work for a giant corporation. I really wanted to work somewhere that I could use my education to do better things for people. The Peace Corps was the perfect next step."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (5/9) "I started my year-and-a-half-long application process for the Peace Corps while I was still a senior at Richmond because I realized my business interests were not traditional."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (4/9) "When I studied International Business and Economics, I was able to pick degree electives for my junior and senior years. I was most interested in courses about economics in developing countries and globalization in the EU."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (3/9) "...for the Peace Corps, made the move to San Francisco, and worked for a startup incubator ‚Äî and then eventually Detroit Labs when I moved back to Michigan (again)."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (2/9) "I am originally from Michigan, but I have moved around a lot in my life. I went to college at Richmond, The American International University in London, to study International Business and Economics, after which I was in DC, then I served in Bulgaria..."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (1/9) Kelsey shares how she got started in the tech world and shows us that there's really no place like home:  https://t.co/LPz2PbjilW

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (7/1) "Learning what it means to build software at a company that values diversity and equity has been an invaluable education and opened my eyes to a world that I had only known as a user."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (6/6) "I honestly hadn't thought about applying my new technical knowledge to my marketing career, but after conversations with leadership, I teamed up with Billy Camp (our late, truly great VP Sales) and we started to figure out what marketing at Labs would look like."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (5/6) "I started to use hack time to market a whiskey app that some of my friends had built and designed here at Labs, and it was really fun!"

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (4/6) "I heard about Detroit Labs and was interested in working here, but I wasn't sure what that would look like. When the apprenticeship came around in 2014, I got into the program and did an intensive year of training and working on a project team."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (3/6) "I began to take classes with Girl Develop It and some online courses that helped build up a modest understanding of how to program, but what it really gave me was the ability to figure out HOW to figure out technical problems."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (2/6) "So, when I would need to do something simple like add a photo of an executive team member to a page, but the changes needed to be made in HTML, I had a lot of trouble. To be honest, solving something like that was really intimidating."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: (1/6) "I'm in marketing, and my background and education were in marketing, but a lot of the technical aspects that marketers have to handle today weren't really taught to comm majors at the time."

name: Detroit Labs
tweet: Today, Elyse shares how she moved from marketing to tech (and back again!) üëâ  https://t.co/zwLaZo3rhW
